O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"modinfo";a:6:{i:5;O:8:"stdClass":11:{s:2:"id";s:1:"5";s:2:"cm";s:1:"5";s:3:"mod";s:5:"forum";s:7:"section";s:1:"0";s:9:"sectionid";s:2:"22";s:6:"module";s:1:"9";s:5:"added";s:10:"1607815228";s:7:"visible";s:1:"1";s:19:"visibleoncoursepage";i:1;s:10:"visibleold";s:1:"1";s:4:"name";s:6:"Avisos";}i:6;O:8:"stdClass":14:{s:2:"id";s:1:"1";s:2:"cm";s:1:"6";s:3:"mod";s:5:"label";s:7:"section";s:1:"1";s:9:"sectionid";s:2:"23";s:6:"module";s:2:"13";s:5:"added";s:10:"1607916537";s:7:"visible";s:1:"1";s:19:"visibleoncoursepage";i:1;s:10:"visibleold";s:1:"1";s:10:"completion";s:1:"1";s:15:"showdescription";s:1:"1";s:4:"name";s:5:"Label";s:7:"content";s:253:"<div class="no-overflow"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/5Jh1I4oRel0" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe></div>";}i:7;O:8:"stdClass":12:{s:2:"id";s:1:"1";s:2:"cm";s:1:"7";s:3:"mod";s:6:"assign";s:7:"section";s:1:"2";s:9:"sectionid";s:2:"24";s:6:"module";s:1:"1";s:5:"added";s:10:"1607916694";s:7:"visible";s:1:"1";s:19:"visibleoncoursepage";i:1;s:10:"visibleold";s:1:"1";s:10:"completion";s:1:"1";s:4:"name";s:12:"Bibliografia";}i:8;O:8:"stdClass":14:{s:2:"id";s:1:"2";s:2:"cm";s:1:"8";s:3:"mod";s:5:"label";s:7:"section";s:1:"2";s:9:"sectionid";s:2:"24";s:6:"module";s:2:"13";s:5:"added";s:10:"1607916786";s:7:"visible";s:1:"1";s:19:"visibleoncoursepage";i:1;s:10:"visibleold";s:1:"1";s:10:"completion";s:1:"1";s:15:"showdescription";s:1:"1";s:4:"name";s:55:"We’ve all seen a huge rise in drone photography ov...";s:7:"content";s:17747:"<div class="no-overflow"><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"><p>We’ve all seen a huge rise in drone photography over the last couple of years, and the quality of work some photographers capture is simply amazing.&nbsp;</p><p>If you want to improve your aerial shots, learning some drone photography 101 is a good place to start.</p><p>In this article I cover the pitfalls I’ve encountered, along with some tips and best practices to help you avoid making costly beginner mistakes.&nbsp; I will also share techniques and camera settings for the more advanced photographers and videographers who’re looking to step-up their drone photography game.&nbsp;</p><h1>PURCHASING YOUR DRONE</h1><p>Drone photography can be tricky, and you’ll find out, pretty quickly, if it’s not for you.&nbsp;&nbsp;A lot of people who buy drones give up almost immediately.&nbsp; That’s why you should be judicious when purchasing your first.&nbsp;&nbsp;Start hunting online for bargains on second-hand drones, where you can save almost fifty percent off the retail price.&nbsp;</p><p>There are a few things to take into consideration when buying a drone.&nbsp;&nbsp;First, you’re definitely going to crash it a few times.&nbsp; So, it’s better to learn how to fly your drone from the beginning.&nbsp; When you’re first starting out, I would recommend getting something in the mid-price range because of the likelihood you’ll crash.&nbsp;&nbsp;I’ve had over half a dozen crashes and although most have been minor, they were still expensive to fix.&nbsp;</p><p>The portability of your drone is also important.&nbsp;&nbsp;The bigger and bulkier, the more likely you’ll leave it at home.&nbsp; Trust me,&nbsp;I speak from experience.&nbsp; That’s why&nbsp;I use a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=dji+mavic+drone&amp;i=electronics&amp;ref=nb_sb_noss_2&amp;_encoding=UTF8&amp;tag=scenicsu-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;linkId=e2abfa1585f2ad43bcd1c58d1dfb10e1&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">DJI Mavic</a>, and love that it folds up to fit into a camera bag.&nbsp;</p><p><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Drone-1024x683.png" alt="A drone flying over the ocean. Drone Photography 101 includes everything you need to know for impressive aerial images and jaw-dropping video footage. From beginner to advanced!" width="1024" height="683" srcset="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Drone.png 1024w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Drone-300x200.png 300w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Drone-768x512.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"></p><p><br></p><h1>PREPARING FOR TAKEOFF</h1><p>Now that you’ve got a drone, it’s time to prepare for flight!&nbsp;</p><p>First and foremost, make sure you follow the civil aviation rules in your country and register your drone if required.</p><p>Next, take some time to familiarize yourself with the controls and leave the settings on beginner mode while you learn.&nbsp;&nbsp;The DJI drones have flying tutorials built into the app, so you can easily learn without even leaving the ground.&nbsp; In fact, it allows you to fly a virtual drone using the controller and your cell phone.</p><p>To further your skills, find drone meet-ups online to meet other drone photographers.&nbsp; It will allow you to learn from more experienced pilots (as well as be more social in the drone photography community!)</p><h1>PLANNING YOUR SHOTS</h1><p>Once you’re familiar with operating your drone, start thinking about what you want to photograph.</p><p>Instead of wandering around, hoping to find a good subject, have an idea about what you want to shoot beforehand.&nbsp; Personally,&nbsp;I take an aerial landscape photographer’s approach.&nbsp;&nbsp;I search&nbsp;for hashtags and locations,&nbsp;and I look at what shots people are taking in the places I’m traveling to.</p><p>Then, I try to capture it with my own style of photography.&nbsp; So if you’ve seen something good, think about how you can improve upon it?&nbsp;</p><p>Finally, I look at Google Maps’ satellite view and plan my shots according to the time of day, lighting conditions, and weather.&nbsp;</p><h2>CHECK THE WEATHER</h2><p>Once I wanted to get a shot of a particular island in New Zealand,&nbsp;and because&nbsp;I didn’t have access to a boat I had to shoot it from land.&nbsp;&nbsp;Using Google Maps, I calculated the distance, which was 3.5km (2.1 miles), and I knew the wind direction, weather conditions, and the forecast for the day.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the wind was too strong, I would never attempt flying that distance and would plan my shoot for another day.&nbsp;</p><p>When they’re in the air, DJI drones will warn you of high winds and instruct you to land as soon as possible.&nbsp; This helps avoid unruly conditions and the loss of your equipment.</p><p><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-1-1024x683.png" alt="An aerial shot of a shipwreck underneath the ocean. Drone Photography 101 includes everything you need to know for impressive aerial images and jaw-dropping video footage. From beginner to advanced!" width="1024" height="683" srcset="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-1.png 1024w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-1-300x200.png 300w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-1-768x512.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"></p><p><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-5-1024x683.png" alt="An aerial shot of a shark that became trapped in a rock pool against the ocean. Drone Photography 101 includes everything you need to know for impressive aerial images and jaw-dropping video footage. From beginner to advanced!" width="1024" height="683" srcset="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-5.png 1024w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-5-300x200.png 300w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-5-768x512.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"></p><h1>FLYING TIPS</h1><p>So you have your drone, you’ve done your prep work, and you’re ready for takeoff!&nbsp; There’s a lot to know when it comes to flying your drone, but here are a few key tips to remember.</p><h2>GPS MODE</h2><p>Always fly in GPS mode to avoid losing your drone.&nbsp; It’s a quick and simple tip that can be a lifesaver when your drone flies out of sight!</p><h2>FLYING OVER WATER</h2><p>When flying over an open body of water like the ocean, always fly into light onshore winds.&nbsp; If you’re fighting strong winds to come back to shore, your drone will have to work harder and deplete the battery until it’s R.I.P. drone.&nbsp;&nbsp;Always check your battery meter and know the limitations of your equipment.&nbsp;</p><p>Another important side note –&nbsp; lithium batteries hate cold weather and die much faster in chilly conditions.&nbsp; So,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=dji+mavic+drone+battery&amp;i=electronics&amp;ref=nb_sb_noss_1&amp;_encoding=UTF8&amp;tag=scenicsu-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;linkId=eefb7b5bb1f60a7a1c566c377a0a7abb&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">plan accordingly</a>!</p><h2>WATCH FOR OBSTACLES</h2><p>Avoiding obstacles is pretty self-explanatory, but what about birds?&nbsp; My drones have, unfortunately, encountered a few bird strikes.&nbsp; That’s because some species of birds are extremely territorial and will try to attack drones.&nbsp;&nbsp;If this happens, fly straight up!&nbsp; Birds can’t fly this way, so it’s impossible for them to chase your drone.&nbsp;&nbsp;I’ve also heard of people using&nbsp;<a href="https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B071V29X6G/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=B071V29X6G&amp;linkCode=undefined&amp;tag=scenicsu-20&amp;linkId=7b0d1145cc3e8c8515f32f6776160309" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">stick-on eye decals</a><img loading="lazy" src="https://ir-na.amazon-adsystem.com/e/ir?t=scenicsu-20&amp;l=am2&amp;o=1&amp;a=B071V29X6G" alt="" width="1" height="1" border="0" data-darkreader-inline-border-top="" data-darkreader-inline-border-right="" data-darkreader-inline-border-bottom="" data-darkreader-inline-border-left="">&nbsp;to deter birds (plus they look cool!)</p><h2>KEEP YOUR COOL</h2><p>If you get into trouble, don’t freak out!&nbsp; Instead, stay calm and think of a solution.&nbsp;</p><p>I once nearly lost a drone filming dolphins off the east coast of Australia when the wind changed and my battery was already at fifty percent.&nbsp;&nbsp;Flying against the wind I realized, pretty quickly, that flying against the wind meant there was a good chance I’d lose my drone.&nbsp;&nbsp;After fighting the headwind and realizing the drone wasn’t moving, I had to think of a different solution.&nbsp;</p><p>I reassessed the problem, looked at the wind direction and velocity, and decided to fly as low as possible where the cliffs and trees provided a windbreak.&nbsp;&nbsp;I then changed direction and flew crosswind to land safely moments later.&nbsp;</p><p><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-3-1024x683.png" alt="Aerial photo of kayaks lined up on the beach. Drone Photography 101 includes everything you need to know for impressive aerial images and jaw-dropping video footage. From beginner to advanced!" width="1024" height="683" srcset="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-3.png 1024w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-3-300x200.png 300w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-3-768x512.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"></p><p><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-6-1024x683.png" alt="An aerial shot of land and ocean. Drone Photography 101 includes everything you need to know for impressive aerial images and jaw-dropping video footage. From beginner to advanced!" width="1024" height="683" srcset="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-6.png 1024w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-6-300x200.png 300w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-6-768x512.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"></p><p><br></p><h1>ADVICE ON SHOOTING STILL PHOTOGRAPHS</h1><p>If you’re looking for technical advice on shooting still photographs with a drone, then I’ve got you covered too!</p><h2>COMPOSITION</h2><p>I shoot a lot of top-down shots, and I like this composition the most.&nbsp;&nbsp;Here are some of my best tips to ensure you get ideal results, every time.</p><p>• Always shoot in RAW (this gives you more control in editing and better print quality)&nbsp;</p><p>• Use Natural Density filters whenever possible (I use&nbsp;<a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Polar+Pro+Cinema+Series+nd+filter+for+DJI+Mavic&amp;i=electronics&amp;ref=nb_sb_noss&amp;_encoding=UTF8&amp;tag=scenicsu-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;linkId=9ae679d0a5d076a57460ad4534e060ed&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">PolarPro Cinema Series</a>)</p><p>• Shoot manual, use the tripod setting, and bracket in post</p><p>• Utilize the HDR settings</p><p>• Use a histogram and zebras to get perfect exposure</p><p>• Download Adobe LR Mobile to edit on vacation&nbsp;<em>(free version)</em></p><h2>BRACKETING</h2><p>Okay, let me explain.&nbsp; Bracketing is when you take multiple shots of the exact same frame.&nbsp;&nbsp;When you do that, you can use Adobe Lightroom or Photoshop to stack them on top of each other and edit them together.</p><p>Why is this beneficial?&nbsp;</p><p>If you shoot in manual, you can take multiple shots with different exposures to maximize the dynamic range of your image.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depending on the time of day and the lighting conditions, certain parts of your image may look better if they’re exposed differently.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Bracketing lets you achieve this easily.&nbsp;&nbsp;Say, for example, I’m shooting a white sandy shoreline at midday.&nbsp;&nbsp;If my exposure is too high, the white sand will be blown out.&nbsp; Or if my exposure is too low, the water will appear darker, less clear, and with more reflections.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>This technique is particularly useful when shooting sunrises, clouds, and sunsets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Some DJI drones have a setting called auto exposure bracketing that does all of this automatically.&nbsp; However, I change the settings myself because I think it gets better results.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are tons of YouTube tutorials on how to accomplish this if you want to learn more.</p><h2>PORTRAIT MODE</h2><p>This is an awesome feature on the Mavic you might not know about.&nbsp;&nbsp;You can actually rotate the camera and capture images in portrait orientation!&nbsp;&nbsp;I capture a lot of my shots this way because the format is favored by Instagram and they look great when printed and framed.&nbsp;</p><h2>TRIPOD MODE, SLOW EXPOSURES, AND TIME-LAPSE</h2><p>The Tripod Mode uses GPS lock to hover in the exact same spot, and allows you to take great slow exposure photos.&nbsp; It’s particularly good for moving objects, water waves, etc.&nbsp; You can even set a long exposure and bracket it for best results!&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>If you want to do a time-lapse of a busy scene, the Tripod Mode will produce amazing images.&nbsp; In addition, including&nbsp;a warp stabilizer effect in post-processing will improve your overall image.&nbsp;&nbsp;Windy conditions may still be noticeable, so avoid breezy days.&nbsp;</p><p><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-4-1024x683.png" alt="An aerial shot of people laying on the beach. Drone Photography 101 includes everything you need to know for impressive aerial images and jaw-dropping video footage. From beginner to advanced!" width="1024" height="683" srcset="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-4.png 1024w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-4-300x200.png 300w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-4-768x512.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"></p><p><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-2-1024x683.png" alt="An aerial shot of beach and rocks with a blue ocean. Drone Photography 101 includes everything you need to know for impressive aerial images and jaw-dropping video footage. From beginner to advanced!" width="1024" height="683" srcset="https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-2.png 1024w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-2-300x200.png 300w, https://www.scenicsuitcase.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Chris-2-768x512.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px"></p><p><br></p><h1>VIDEOGRAPHY</h1><p>If you’re someone that shoots a lot of video, then I’ve got some great ideas for you too!</p><p>I like to shoot cinematic sequences of really picturesque locations.&nbsp;&nbsp;And, I’ve found that controlling camera movement, timing, and setting is the best way to achieve the desired results.</p><h2>SETTINGS</h2><p>I always shoot 4K UHD 3840 x 2160 resolution at 24fps 1/50 shutter speed.&nbsp; Note that ND filters may be required, depending on the lighting conditions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, I shoot in the cine-like profile and have my settings dialed-&nbsp;in to my preferences.&nbsp; Then, during filming, I mostly use auto white balance and change the style settings as follows: -2 sharpness, -2 contrast, and -2 saturation.&nbsp;</p><p>Personally, I use the file format .mov because I’m a Mac user, but .mp4 is better for Windows PC.&nbsp; And,&nbsp;I set my tilt controls to get a really smooth, fluid, head style tilt up and down.&nbsp;</p><h2>SLOW TILT-UP&nbsp;REVEAL</h2><p>A nice, slow tilt-up reveal looks really cinematic, especially over water!&nbsp; You can see a few examples of that in the video below.&nbsp; So, harness your inner Michael Bay and&nbsp;get out there!</p><h2>DON’T USE AUTO EXPOSURE</h2><p>One thing that will make your footage look totally amateur is auto exposure.&nbsp;&nbsp;If you shoot in auto, the changing light conditions will be visible as the exposure changes to compensate.&nbsp;&nbsp;This looks terrible, so don’t do it!&nbsp;</p><h2>AVOID LENS FLARES</h2><p>Don’t get me wrong – I’m a big advocate of lens flares – but, they look&nbsp;<em>terrible</em>&nbsp;on drones and cell phones.&nbsp; This is because those cameras don’t have an adjustable aperture with blades, which give those nice, cine-prime hexagonal or circular cinematic flares.&nbsp; It looks totally amateur on a drone unless you’re flying something expensive, in which case, you don’t need this article.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><h2>USE DOLLY ZOOM IN POST</h2><p>A popular cinematic technique is to use a dolly zoom or vertigo effect.&nbsp; You can accomplish this in post-processing by putting a 4K video on a 1080p timeline and zooming in as you push out.&nbsp;&nbsp;The end result looks really great!&nbsp;</p><h2>COLOR GRADE YOUR FOOTAGE</h2><p>I grade my footage in a REC 709 custom LUT, which pushes a slightly desaturated orange and teal.&nbsp; Then,&nbsp;I edit in Adobe Creative Suite Premiere Pro/After Effects for my f stop.</p><br></p></div>";}i:9;O:8:"stdClass":12:{s:2:"id";s:1:"1";s:2:"cm";s:1:"9";s:3:"mod";s:4:"chat";s:7:"section";s:1:"3";s:9:"sectionid";s:2:"25";s:6:"module";s:1:"4";s:5:"added";s:10:"1607916884";s:7:"visible";s:1:"1";s:19:"visibleoncoursepage";i:1;s:10:"visibleold";s:1:"1";s:10:"completion";s:1:"1";s:4:"name";s:9:"Charlemos";}i:10;O:8:"stdClass":12:{s:2:"id";s:1:"6";s:2:"cm";s:2:"10";s:3:"mod";s:6:"survey";s:7:"section";s:1:"4";s:9:"sectionid";s:2:"26";s:6:"module";s:2:"20";s:5:"added";s:10:"1607917061";s:7:"visible";s:1:"1";s:19:"visibleoncoursepage";i:1;s:10:"visibleold";s:1:"1";s:10:"completion";s:1:"1";s:4:"name";s:8:"Encuesta";}}s:12:"sectioncache";a:5:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:2:"id";s:2:"22";s:4:"name";N;s:12:"availability";N;}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:2:"id";s:2:"23";s:4:"name";N;s:12:"availability";N;}i:2;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:2:"id";s:2:"24";s:4:"name";N;s:12:"availability";N;}i:3;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:2:"id";s:2:"25";s:4:"name";N;s:12:"availability";N;}i:4;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:2:"id";s:2:"26";s:4:"name";N;s:12:"availability";N;}}s:9:"shortname";s:6:"Drones";s:8:"fullname";s:21:"Fotografia con Drones";s:6:"format";s:6:"topics";s:16:"enablecompletion";s:1:"1";s:9:"groupmode";s:1:"0";s:14:"groupmodeforce";s:1:"0";s:8:"cacherev";s:10:"1607917063";}